content.description: You can't miss this from the trail, faces north, splitter fingers for maybe 25 feet or so.  This is the first climb you'll see as you approach the Dinner Table area from the north by trail.
crux is the beginning, then eases up.  Cupped hands/fists to wider
content.location: continue on trail around and behind the 10a finger crack, and head left and slightly down into the large boulders.  watch for poison oak

content.description:
Pretty consistent long (for the area) face climbing, and you can make it harder by sneaking out right - make sure to put your "variations" on MP as an FA.

If you don't like glue, don't climb this one LOL!
content.protection: 2 bomber bolts on top for a TR
content.location: Across from the finger crack, which you shouldn't know about or be at, by the way.

content.description:
The whole thing is the crux.  Actually, the crux is probably trying to get your iphone to balance in the tree branch because you can't find the cheap Chinese-made tripod you bought on Amazon.

There are lots of ways to climb this - lieback like a sporto, or dig deep and jam it.  The fistjam before the lip will make you smile.
content.protection: TR anchor with 4-5" cams, or just be a real local and do it with no rope
content.location: A stone's throw from the Dining Room table, if you know where that is...or what it's really called.

content.description: right leaning big hands/fists, semiflat landing.  Good boulder or short trad lead.  TR is possible but odd with gear
content.location: If you're on top of the 10a finger crack in this area, look across to the north to see an enormous boulder.  There's an old trail around the right of that boulder that heads slightly downhill, this boulder is just behind the huge one.
